# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# WHAT IS VORPAL AND WHY IS IT THE 60TH TS-NODE CLI LIBRARY?
#
# Vorpal (https://github.com/dthree/vorpal, 5,632+ stars) is **David
# Caccavella's "Node's framework for interactive CLIs"** — the dominant
# Node.js library for building REPL-style interactive shells.  Where
# commander/yargs/oclif/cac/meow/sade/mri/minimist/clipanion/gluegun/
# stricli all assume "user invokes `mybin subcommand --flag` and the
# program exits", Vorpal assumes "user invokes `mybin` and gets an
# interactive prompt that accepts commands until the user exits".
#
# Vorpal's distinguishing characteristics:
#
#   1. REPL-FIRST PROGRAM MODEL — Vorpal's central feature is that
#      every Vorpal app is an interactive shell prompt:
#
#          const Vorpal = require('vorpal');
#          const vorpal = new Vorpal();
#
#          vorpal
#              .command('ls [path]', 'List directory contents')
#              .alias('dir')
#              .option('-l, --long', 'long-format listing')
#              .option('-a, --all', 'show hidden files')
#              .action(function (args, callback) {
#                  // `this` is the vorpal session
#                  this.log(`Listing ${args.path || '.'}`);
#                  callback();
#              });
#
#          vorpal.delimiter('myshell$').show();
#          // → Drops into interactive prompt:
#          //   myshell$ ls -la /etc
#          //   myshell$ help
#          //   myshell$ exit
#
#      Compare:
#         * commander: program.parse() exits after one invocation
#         * yargs: yargs.parse() exits after one invocation
#         * oclif: per-command class, single execution model
#         * Python cmd module: similar REPL model but no
#                                autocomplete / no aliases
#         * vorpal: REPL-FIRST with every commander-style command
#                    inside the REPL
#      FIRST documented Node.js CLI framework with REPL-first
#      program model.
#
#   2. BUILT-IN TAB-AUTOCOMPLETE FOR COMMANDS + ARGS — Vorpal
#      auto-tab-completes registered commands + per-command
#      argument values via `.autocomplete()`:
#
#          vorpal
#              .command('cd <path>', 'Change directory')
#              .autocomplete({
#                  data: function () {
#                      return fs.readdirSync('.')
#                          .filter(f => fs.statSync(f).isDirectory());
#                  }
#              })
#              .action(function (args, callback) {
#                  process.chdir(args.path);
#                  callback();
#              });
#
#          // User types: cd <TAB>
#          // → Vorpal autocompletes from current directory's
#          //   subdirectories
#
#      Compare:
#         * commander: no autocomplete (requires user to set up
#                       shell completion separately)
#         * yargs: shell completion via yargs-completion plugin
#         * oclif: shell completion via @oclif/plugin-autocomplete
#         * Python cmd: completion via per-command complete_*
#                        methods (less ergonomic)
#         * Python prompt_toolkit: rich autocomplete (closest
#                                    analog)
#         * vorpal: BUILT-IN per-command autocomplete via data()
#      FIRST documented Node.js CLI framework with per-command
#      runtime autocomplete as a built-in primitive.
#
#   3. MODE COMMANDS — vorpal.mode() — Vorpal supports SUB-
#      SHELLS WITHIN THE SHELL — entering "mode" changes the
#      prompt + restricts available commands until "exit":
#
#          vorpal
#              .mode('sql')
#              .description('SQL mode')
#              .delimiter('sql>')
#              .action(function (command, callback) {
#                  // command is the raw SQL string typed
#                  this.log(`Executing: ${command}`);
#                  callback();
#              });
#
#          // User session:
#          //   myshell$ sql
#          //   sql> SELECT * FROM users;
#          //   sql> SELECT count(*) FROM orders;
#          //   sql> exit
#          //   myshell$
#
#      This is the FIRST-CLASS sub-shell primitive — no other
#      documented Node.js CLI library has this.  Compare:
#         * commander/yargs/oclif: program exits per invocation
#         * Python cmd: precmd / postcmd hooks but no mode
#         * Python prompt_toolkit: layered Application instances
#                                    (manual)
#         * vorpal: .mode() with auto delimiter change
#      FIRST documented Node.js CLI framework with sub-shell
#      mode commands as a first-class API.
#
#   4. REMOTE SHELL SERVING — vorpal can SERVE its REPL over
#      WebSocket / TCP for remote administration of long-running
#      Node.js processes (similar to Erlang's remote shell or
#      Common Lisp's SLIME):
#
#          const vorpal = new Vorpal();
#          vorpal.command('status').action(function (args, callback) {
#              this.log(`uptime: ${process.uptime()}s`);
#              callback();
#          });
#          vorpal.listen(3000);  // serve REPL over WebSocket on :3000
#
#          // Then connect from another machine:
#          //   const client = require('vorpal-client');
#          //   client.connect({ port: 3000, host: 'prod.example.com' });
#
#      Compare:
#         * commander/yargs/oclif: no remote shell support
#         * Erlang: built-in remote shell (rpc:call)
#         * Common Lisp: SLIME REPL
#         * Python: code.interact() but no remoting
#         * vorpal: vorpal-server + vorpal-client packages for
#                    WebSocket/TCP remote REPL
#      FIRST documented Node.js CLI framework with remote-shell
#      serving as a documented use case.
#
#   5. DTHREE / DAVID-CACCAVELLA ECOSYSTEM PROVENANCE — Vorpal
#      is by David Caccavella (dthree on GitHub) who built a
#      family of related interactive-CLI packages:
#         * vorpal — main framework
#         * cash (THIS) — UNIX commands via vorpal
#         * vorpal-less — `less` paginator inside vorpal
#         * vorpal-grep — `grep` inside vorpal
#         * vorpal-log — vorpal-aware logger
#         * vorpal-server — WebSocket REPL server
#         * vorpal-client — WebSocket REPL client
#         * vorpal-tour — interactive guided-tour mode
#         * vorpal-repl — embed Node REPL inside vorpal
#         * vorpal-watch — watch-mode for vorpal
#         * 50+ community vorpal-* plugins
#      Downstream users:
#         * dthree/cash (THIS — 7.7k stars)
#         * tintinweb/solidity-shell (541 stars)
#         * JGAntunes/ipfs-chat
#         * berlioz-the/berlioz
#         * GeekyAnts/reazy
#         * freewheel/dashflow
#         * jtangelder/denon-remote
#         * many smaller REPL-based tools
#      FIRST documented Node.js CLI framework with this specific
#      David-Caccavella ecosystem provenance + 50+ vorpal-*
#      official plugin family.
#
# Vorpal's relationship to other documented Node.js CLI frameworks:
#
#   * Unlike commander — commander assumes one-shot invocation;
#                          vorpal assumes interactive REPL
#   * Unlike yargs — yargs assumes one-shot; vorpal assumes REPL
#   * Unlike oclif — oclif assumes one-shot subcommand classes
#   * Unlike cac/meow/sade/mri/minimist — minimal one-shot parsers
#   * Unlike clipanion/gluegun/stricli — declarative one-shot
#   * Closest cross-language analogs:
#         * Python: cmd module (stdlib) + cmd2 + prompt_toolkit
#         * Go: abiosoft/ishell + chzyer/readline
#         * Rust: rustyline + reedline + clap-repl
#         * Erlang: built-in shell + rpc remoting
#         * Common Lisp: SLIME interactive REPL
#     Vorpal is the FIRST documented Node.js library providing
#     REPL-first + tab-autocomplete + mode subshells + remote
#     shell serving as a unified interactive CLI framework.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# THE cash CLI — vorpal + 22 UNIX commands + delimiter + interceptor
#
# cash's CLI is in bin/cash.js → src/index.js.  Bin entry:
#
#     #!/usr/bin/env node
#     'use strict';
#     var cash = require('../dist/index');
#     var delimiter = require('./../dist/delimiter')
#     delimiter.refresh(cash.vorpal, function () {
#         cash.show();
#     });
#
# src/index.js instantiates a Vorpal app + loads 22 UNIX command
# implementations from src/commands/<cmd>.js + registers each
# with vorpal:
#
#     const Vorpal = require('vorpal');
#     const app = {
#         commands: ['alias', 'cat', 'cd', 'clear', 'cp', 'echo',
#                    'head', 'export', 'false', 'kill', 'ls',
#                    'mkdir', 'mv', 'pwd', 'sort', 'source',
#                    'tail', 'touch', 'true', 'less', 'grep',
#                    'rm', 'unalias', 'which'],
#         vorpal: new Vorpal(),
#         ...
#     };
#
# Two binaries shipped (per package.json `bin` field):
#     "$"    → ./bin/cash.js  (dollar-sign alias)
#     "cash" → ./bin/cash.js  (canonical name)
#
# Interactive shell — once `cash` is invoked, the program runs
# inside the vorpal REPL until the user types `exit` or sends
# EOF (Ctrl-D).
#
# Five-axis distinctness from every other Node.js CLI framework:
#
#   1. REPL-FIRST PROGRAM MODEL — Every other documented Node.js
#      CLI framework is one-shot.  Vorpal is REPL-first.
#
#   2. BUILT-IN PER-COMMAND TAB-AUTOCOMPLETE — Every other Node.js
#      CLI framework requires external shell-completion setup.
#      Vorpal has built-in runtime per-command autocomplete.
#
#   3. MODE COMMANDS / SUB-SHELLS — Every other Node.js CLI
#      framework lacks sub-shell mode primitives.  Vorpal has
#      first-class .mode() commands.
#
#   4. REMOTE SHELL SERVING — Every other Node.js CLI framework
#      lacks remote-REPL serving.  Vorpal has vorpal-server +
#      vorpal-client for WebSocket/TCP remoting.
#
#   5. DAVID-CACCAVELLA + 50+ PLUGIN ECOSYSTEM — Every other
#      documented Node.js CLI framework has different ecosystem.
#      Vorpal is by dthree with 50+ vorpal-* official plugins.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# COMMAND-LINE OPTIONS
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Note: cash launches an interactive vorpal REPL.  Once inside the
# shell, the 22 built-in commands (cat/cd/ls/cp/mv/rm/etc.) accept
# their own flags via vorpal's command parser.  Top-level invocation
# is:  cash             → interactive shell
#      $    (alias)     → interactive shell
#      cash --help      → help text (vorpal default)
#      cash --version   → version (vorpal default)
# Built-in commands inside the REPL are NOT shell completions — they
# are tab-completed by vorpal itself once you are inside the prompt.

local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1
typeset -A opt_args

_arguments -C \
    '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
    '(- *)--version[show version]' \
    && ret=0

return ret
